General Description: 3” gas operated, semi-automatic tactical shotgun that allows you to shoot light to heavy loads. Removable choke system that uses Beretta® Mobile threads includes one choke tube (Extended). Highly durable injection molded stock w/ fixed pistol grip and forearm. The Raptor ATAC features a picatinny rail and ghost ring sight mounted, plus a fiber optic bridge front sight, fixed pistol grip stock with soft rubber gripping and swivel studs.  Features:Magazine Cut-OffBridge Front Sight with Fiber Optic BeadPicatinny Rail with Ghost Ring Sight Mounted5 Round MagazineChrome-lined Chamber and BarrelSwivel StudsExtended Beretta® Mobile Choke Action: Gas operated semi-automatic. Bolt remains open after last round is fired. If magazine and chamber are both loaded, opening action will result in ejecting shell from chamber but will not cycling new shell from magazine into the chamber. Magazine cut-off is located near trigger guard and must be pushed to eject shell from magazine. This allows shooter to clear chamber but keep magazine loaded. Safety: The primary safety is located on the backside of the trigger guard. When engaged, the safety is designed to block the trigger, hammer lever and the hammer which makes the firing mechanism immobile. Magazine: Tubular magazine; bottom loading.

title: For Sale:  Marlin 1881 Deluxe .32-40
postcontent: MARLIN 1881 DELUXE RIFLE FACTORY ENGRAVED BY NIMSCHKE! General Specs: Marlin Arms, Year 1888, .32-40, 8lbs 5oz, Lever Rifle Serial Number: 16681 What an incredible piece of history we have before us in this antique Marlin Deluxe special order rifle.  Can you imagine ordering a gun like this in 1887 and taking delivery at the local general store in February 1888?  What the town's people must have thought, and what pride of ownership the gent must have had.  This is a very rare example of John Marlin's first lever action repeating rifle, with only 16,378 made.  The Cody Firearms Museum letter gives us the basics; Model 1881, .32-40 caliber, 28" barrel, shipped 1888.  As noted in Colonel Brophy's seminal book on Marlin guns entitled "MARLIN FIREARMS --- A History of the Guns and the Company That Made Them", the early records did not record whether the guns were ordered with engraving, or other special order features.  However, the gun does speak for itself, and we know that it was ordered on the small frame used for the .32-40 and the .38-55 with the special ordered heavy octagon barrel, that it was ordered with Deluxe grade English walnut, factory checkered buttstock and forend, a Lyman Ivory Bead front sight, and factory engraving.  Louis Daniel Nimschke is given credit in Brophy's book for most all of the engraved 1881 rifles, and if you look at the hand of the engraving, it is definitively Nimschke's signature scroll and game scenes.  Only 1785 of these rifles were made in the .32-40 caliber, and only 1303 with pistol grip butt stocks.  Only a tiny handful were factory engraved.  BEST OF ALL---THIS RIFLE IS UNTOUCHED AND RETAINS 45% FADING FACTORY CASE COLOR, 95% FACTORY BLUE, AND MOST ALL OF THE FACTORY WOOD FINISHES!  The factory checkering has never been recut, and the bore is mirror shiny with all of the rifling crisp and clear, the screws are in excellent condition, and there is no pitting inside or out. The mechanics are crisp and excellent in all ways. I am offering this historic rifle at a very modest price making it a great investment opportunity and fleeting chance to own a piece of history at a bargain price.  DON'T LET THIS ONE GET AWAY! Barrels Barrel Length: 28" special order heavy barrel Bores: excellent mirror bore % Blue: 97% factory Sights: Lyman #1 tang Action Action: clean and tight  Case Color: 45% factory faded Screws: excellent Engraving: factory engraved Louis Nimschke Trigger Type: crisp Stock Type: "S" style pistol grip, english walnut LOP: 13 3/8" LOP To End Of Wood: 13" Checkering Condition: excellent factory untouched Butt Treatment: crescent steel butt plate Best way to contact for speedy reply is by phone 928-362-8844(text only). title: For Sale:  7.62x39 Molot Vepr Pre AG Ban
postcontent: For sale is one of the first rifles I bought when I moved back to MA in 2014.  This is a Molot Vepr in 7.62x39 with the slant-back receiver and RPK style trunnion, receiver, and thicker barrel.  It's a bit heavy for an AK-patterned rifle, but the thicker barrel allows for more accurate shots.  Last year these were banned from import from Russia with the second round of sanctions so sadly they'll probably become like the Norinco rifles.Attached to the muzzle end is a SRVV Jet Brake, also manufactured in Russia.  This has been pinned and spot welded for MA compliancy and signfificantly helps with recoil, which is still mild due to the rifle's weight.  Included are 13 30rd pre-ban magazines (5 Yugo bolt hold open, and 8 standard) as well as 2 40rd pre-ban magazines from eastern europe.  I'm also including some russian RPK handguards, a molot pistol grip, and the RPK handguard retainer made by Dinzag Arms.  The gas tube is also made by Dinzag Arms to allow for the installation of the top handguard.  I've also installed an ALG Defense trigger that makes shooting this a dream.  Nice short, crisp trigger pull with a short reset.I am not including any ammo as I still shoot it with other rifles, and it's cheap enough to find.I'm looking to move and am not taking this rifle with me, so I'm looking to sell it to someone who can appreciate it here in MA.  I'll use an E-FA 10 since it's definitely not allowed by the AG with the current laws, though it has still been granfathered into the old laws.  I'm looking for $2800 for everything and will meet up at The Gun Parlor in Worcester to make the transaction. I am not looking for trades, and low-offers will be ignored.  Molot makes some of the nicest AK-patterned rifles available and it's a shame we won't see any imported into the country for the forseeable future.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mint Grade Chilean Mauser 1895
postcontent:
This is a seemingly unissued, low serial number Chilean contract Mauser Chileno Modelo 1895, manufactured in Lowe, Berlin. Mauser collectors, hold on to your hats!
 
WARTIME FIREARMS, LLC – WE SHIP!!!
(NO FFL REQUIRED FOR THE SHIPPING OF THIS ANTIQUE FIREARM)
 
Very seldom do these come up for sale in this condition, especially at this price point. If you’re a serious collector, this is the Mauser for you… A near-mint early serial number (A6201) rifle. Even the cleaning rod is original and serialized to the gun! Starting off with the stock, it is in overall great condition, with less than typical storage markings and no wear and tear from use. The cartouches are all there – the matching serial number with the star of David below it, the arrowhead behind the trigger guard, the four-leaf clover behind the rear sling mount, and the 1895 crest on the butt. There’s nothing to say about the bluing on this rifle, other than it being 100% with NO visible flaws at all. The Chilean crest on the receiver is beautifully stamped and visible. The original barrel is in shocking condition – this rifle was rarely shot during its 123-year existence. The bolt is smooth as butter and still has some cosmoline on it from storage.
 
Folks, there is no rifle that compares in quality to a near brand-new Mauser from 1895. The Mauser rifle was the precursor to almost every great bolt-action firearm today, and not without good reason. Just one minute of holding this rifle and you will instantly become a fan of it, and the Mauser line of rifles in general. To put it bluntly, this is the Bugatti of the bolt-action world.
 
This rifle is priced to sell at $1195 – make an offer, we entertain trades!
